The Southwest region is unarguably endowed with vast arable land and human resources that can be cultivated to produce sufficient food for the region and other parts of the country. [FILE PHOTO] Tractor  She said: “Most of the structures set up are not placed under good management as management is allotted based on favoritism. The handling of agric initiatives in the region is also shoddy, while states in the Southwest usually politicised the initiatives, the north is focused on the beneficiaries getting all that they needed.”  She said: “Cooling supplies for perishable goods can also be installed in trucks to keep perishable food products fresh. Incubators should also be acquired to enhance poultry farming.”
  
The Head of Farmers in Imeko, Ogun State, Chief Ismail Abolore, said the region has continued to experience a series of challenges, despite efforts by farmers to sustain productivity.  “The closure of our land borders is supposed to be a blessing to the country and farmers, but the reverse is the case, as many factors have eroded the gains such as climate change, COVID-19 pandemic, government somersaulting policies, dearth of good infrastructure, lack of modern farm tool to improve food production, alleged insincerity by state governments to issue Certificate of Occupancy (CoO) to farmers and lack of adequate funds. 